\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Extraction of harmonic partials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harmonic sinusoidal model of [Serra] filters the spectral components
 corresponding to a source with fundamental frequency.
 Parabolic interpolation is used for locating the peaks corresponding to
 the the harmonics 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{n}\approx h_{n}f^{0}$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the harmonic index.
 This gives a more accurate estimate of the peak locations and amplitudes.
 We estimate the first 30 harmonics in order to exploit the instability
 of the vocal pitch at higher harmonics as compared to other instruments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vocal Variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Singing voice can be distinguished for its continuous timbre: When singers
 articulate actual words, the variation of the spectral envelope is more
 pronounced than for most other instruments [
\color orange
ref
\color inherit
].
 To approximate the spectral shape, MFCCs have been widely utilized, because
 they relate well to changes of the vocal tract shape.
 Features that describe spectral dynamics over time proved to contribute
 to the SVD problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rao2011context,lehner2014reduction"

\end_inset

.
 Due to the application of DCT as a last step of computing MFCCs, the first
 few coefficients represent the slow variations of spectrum [Rabiner and
 Huang].
 We utilize the variance of the first 5 MFCCs adopting the frame and hop
 size of 800 and 200 ms, suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
